3.Explain superblock with respect to Linux filesystem\par
A superblock refers to a record of the attributes of a filesystem, which includes its size, the block size, the empty and the filled blocks and their respective counts, the size and location of the inode tables, the disk block map, and usage information, and finally the size of the block groups.\par
Therefore superblock is typically stored on the storage medium but can be created in real time if one doesn't exist hence one can find the superblock structure in ./linux/include/Linux/fs.h.\par
In this structure, the set of functions for managing inodes within the file system is defined. For example, inodes can be allocated with alloc_inode or deleted with destroy_inode. You can read and write inodes with read_inode and write_inode or sync the file system with sync_fs.One can find the super_operations structure in ./linux/include/linux/fs.h. Each file system supplies its own inode methods, that implement the operations and supply the common abstraction to the VFS layer.\par
A superblock in many filesystems denotes a disk block that contains some vital information about the rest of the filesystem. therefore without the superblock, one cannot mount the filesystem, and since it's so important, there are usually multiple and unnecessary copies of the superblock stored on the filesystem for recovery. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.quora.com/In-a-Linux-file-system-what-is-a-Superblock"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1 https://www.quora.com/In-a-Linux-file-system-what-is-a-Superblock}}}\f0\fs22  \par
4.      Research about IPv6 and describe the key reasons behind its design and implementation. How is it more secure then IPv4?\par
IPv6 refers to Internet Protocol version, which is the most recent version of the Internet Protocol (IP), it is the communications protocol that provides an identification and location system for computers on networks and routes traffic across the Internet. \par
It was developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) mainly to deal with the long-anticipated problem of IPv4 address exhaustion. IPv6 is therefore intended to replace IPv4. IPv6, in this case, became a Draft Standard in December 1998, and further became an Internet Standard on 14 July 2017. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPv6"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPv6}}}\f0\fs22\par
its implementation  has been through configuration  mainly on Cisco routers 2800, Windows\par
Server 2012, Windows 8, Windows 7 and finally on MAC OS X.\par
The Cisco devices running the IOS 12.2(2) and later version support IPv6.\par
However, in Cisco routers, IPv6 services are not enabled by default. Hence the\par
IPv6 services have to be manually enabled by using ipv6 unicast-routing\par
from global configuration mode as shown below:\par
rack5_ROUTER_2800 (config)#ipv6 unicast-routing\par
After  the  enable of IPv6 services on the routers, IPv6 addresses have been\par
configured to each interface. Both the global as well as link-local addresses\par
have been assigned as static addresses. The  commands (eg rack5_ROUTER_2800(config-if)# ipv6 enable )have\par
been issued at the interface mode.\par
Followed by the interface configuration, show ipv6 interface brief command\par
has been issued to verify the configuration. whereas, to check the basic\par
connectivity between the interfaces of the router ping commands such as(rack5_ROUTER_2800#show ipv6 interface brief)  have been issued. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theseus.fi/bitstream/handle/10024/71524/IPv6_final_thesis.pdf?...1"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1 https://www.theseus.fi/bitstream/handle/10024/71524/IPv6_final_thesis.pdf?...1}}}\f0\fs22\par
\b How IPv6 is more secure than IPv4\b0\par
The IPv6 protocol has solved some, although not all, of the security problems found in IPv4 networks. One example is the mandatory inclusion of IP Security (IPsec) in the IPv6 protocol, making it fundamentally more secure than the older IPv4 standard. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://thebestvpn.com/ipv4-vs-ipv6/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1 https://thebestvpn.com/ipv4-vs-ipv6/}}}\f0\fs22\par
